450.technical_description:
Ankylosing spondylitis&nbsp;(AS)&nbsp;together with rheumatoid arthritis are the two most common rheumatic-type diseases in the general population, with a prevalence of AS&nbsp;for the European population of 0.23%.&nbsp;AS&nbsp;is usually classified as an axial spondyloarthropathy and presents primarily with chronic back pain,&nbsp;arthritis bilaterally and of the sacroiliac joints and lumbosacral spine.&nbsp;AS onset is around&nbsp;the age of 40.&nbsp;Symptoms may improve with exercise but not with rest and are usually more bothersome at night.&nbsp;

Only 4% of the European population has one copy of the B27 allele (rs4349859 AG genotype) according to the Ensembl database. This allele is highly prevalent in males with AS. HLA-B27 is present in 8% of the healthy Caucasian population and 90% of AS patients. However, only 1 to 5% of individuals positive for HLA-B27 develop AS, suggesting that other genetic factors are involved (Evans et al., 2011).&nbsp;

Recent studies in animal models suggest that HLA-B27 could have an interaction with the gut microbiota (microbial community&nbsp;from the gut) that may have a role in AS pathogenesis and other related symptoms in AS patients as intestinal inflammation&nbsp;(Dumas et al., 2020;&nbsp;Gill&nbsp;and&nbsp;Rosenbaum, 2021).&nbsp;

